<br>
<br>
“Cast all your anxiety on him because he cares for you”  1 Peter 5:7<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I missed this class, but am working towards my degree via real life experience.  Take today for instance…..<br>
<br>
It all began about 10:30 a.m. during our normal morning routine.  I was on the treadmill with visions of a leaner, toner body on mind, the baby was fast asleep dreaming of sugar-plum fairies and Ben was playing with his new foam cars dreaming of being a ‘struction man while watching Mr. Rogers.<br>
<br>
By 10:50, Ben had a new dream:  to see how far up his nose he could insert a piece of foam.  Yes, that would be a torn off piece of foam from his new car.  Now, as far as I know, neither Mr. Rogers nor the Teletubbies have ever done this trick—do the tubbies even have noses?  Anyway, I am certain that this was a Ben T original idea.<br>
<br>
Carrying my crying, rapidly becoming hysterical child upstairs, I take him to the bathroom to scope out the situation.  “Sit here while I find the flashlight”, I tell him.  Returning with the extra light to shine up his nostril, I spot the glowing piece of yellow foam.  Ah, I can grab that with my tweezers.<br>
<br>
I must have thought this audibly because at the mention of tweezers, my pre-schooler screamed and shouted, “No!”  Holding him and reassuring him that all would be fine, I coax him into breathing through his mouth and blowing very hard out his nose.  A few good blows and that thing will come flying out I thought.  Problem was, Ben doesn’t blow his nose like the rest of the population.  In fact, you could hardly label it as blowing at all.  He refuses to close his mouth entirely, so therefore the mucous and other nasty debris remain, while healthy wads of saliva come flying forth.  Again and again we tried, but alas, you can lead a child to tissues but you can’t make them blow.<br>
<br>
Ben is still crying and out of control while I go to search for my tweezers.  By this time, my previous stable—if you could even call it that—frame of mind was waning.  I search my bathroom drawers frantically looking for the coveted tweezers.  Tweezers, tweezers, WHERE ARE THE  @#!%* TWEEZERS!  ….Oh, right.  I always carry them in my make-up bag…..here they are.  With Ben still crying and shaking, I lay him down on a bath towel, wipe the tears away and tell him what I am about to attempt.  With a 50lb., 100 watt flashlight in one hand and the tweezers in the other, I begin.  “Hold your head like so…..can you push your nostril up like this Ben?” ….oh, this will never work.  Giving up the flashlight, I push his nose up with one hand, go in with the other and all the while telling Ben the story from my childhood.  The one where I stuck a Pez up my nose.<br>
<br>
After a few minutes or maybe it was seconds of this, I see that I am getting nowhere.  After an hour I have been through every imaginable emotion mothers know.  And all without the aid of PMS or Steel Magnolias.  Ben is still crying and it doesn’t help when I tell him that his nose will continue to swell the more he cries.  It also doesn’t help when I tell him we will have to go to the hospital if mommy can’t get the foam out.  After a brief chat with Will—the calm parent—I decide to give it a rest.  He is not in a life threatening situation, and to sit down, read a book or watch Arthur, or Clifford the Big Red Dog, maybe Ben will calm down.  This works!  In fact, it worked so well that Ben decided having a piece of foam up your nose wasn’t such a bad thing after all.<br>
<br>
All was quiet and calm again so I took a shower, fed the baby and made myself a peanut butter and jelly sandwich.  After an hour or so Ben is breathing through his mouth, he is calm, NOW maybe I can take another look and see if I can pry that thing out.  Ben is NOT cooperative.  Fortunately, he wants a peanut butter and jelly too.  “You can’t have a sandwich until you let mommy pull that thing out of your nose.”  (Now, that statement belongs in every Parenting 101 class).  He refuses, gets all upset AGAIN, and the tears flow forth.<br>
<br>
Another brief chat with Will yields a new idea—close off his ears, hold the clear nostril closed and blow hard through his mouth.  I actually did this.  It may work for some kids with erasers up their nose, but not Ben.  It must have to do with the weight of the object or something.  Maybe if I could get him to sneeze it would come flying out! “Brilliant idea Amy”, I thought to myself as I led my trusting little one outdoors.  “Here, stand right in the sunlight…..let me blow some of these dandelion seeds on you too…”  “ACHOO!” …..nothing.  “ACHOO!” ……again, no flying yellow foam.<br>
<br>
I am frustrated to the point of tears now, wanting to help my son, wanting to shield him from a scary situation at the hospital, and wanting to run out the door and not look back!  Ok, we have to go the doctor’s office NOW.<br>
<br>
I am chewing my nails and scurrying down the road to make it to the clinic by 3:30.  I’m making good time, ….making good time…Oh!  School Bus!  I am tempted to put my emergency flashers on at this point but figured if an officer of the law pulled me over he would never believe my story.  Partly because Ben and baby Josie are sleeping like angels in the back seat.  I calm down and think good thoughts, pray for help and wait for an opportunity to PASS THAT BUS.  Did I mention it was raining buckets at this time?<br>
<br>
We make it on time and I am searching for Will as he agreed to meet me there.  No Blue Blazer.  How can that BE?  He left way before me.  I call him on the cell phone and discover he is banking.  Oh, please get me a lollipop while you’re there and WOULD YOU GET HERE ASAP- YOU KNOW BEN HAS A PIECE OF FOAM UP HIS NOSE!<br>
<br>
Will arrives in about two minutes.  We take Ben inside, sign his name and I leave him in Will’s care.  Josie needs fed by this time and actually, I am more upset than Ben at this point.<br>
<br>
I wait in the truck for what seems like hours, but was probably only thirty minutes.  Next thing I know, here comes Ben with a tear-stained face and a purple lollipop in his hand.  The foam is gone, Ben can breathe, I can breathe and Will has earned a merit badge for going in the room to watch a doctor and 4 Storm Troopers hold Ben down and pull a piece of foam from his nose.<br>
<br>
He didn’t get to keep the foam.  I imagine the good doctor has a little box under her desk labeled “Items Removed From Kids’ Noses”.  Something akin to the fascination people have with the contents of sharks’ stomachs.  As far as post-foam removal treatment, the doctor suggested Tylenol—she forgot my Valium.<br>
<br>
I can assure you that Ben has learned a valuable lesson here, as this is what I heard him say to a little boy in the waiting room, “Do you know what will happen if you stick something up your nose?”  ….silence……”You’ll have to go to the doctor and let ‘em get it out.”<br>
<br>
All I want to know is, do I get an “A” for surviving this, or is this new grey hair my badge of honor?<br>
<br>
