<br>
I have a few of my own, the best is being on a first name basis with the 'poison control center' for Sarah (my eldest) 1st taking a bite of stick deodorant.  2nd eating a packet of sillica, you know the stuff they use to keep electronics dry? Comes in a little packet.  There were others, but the best one was this.....<br>
<br>
I was going out with a girlfriend, a night out for mom.  My husband was working and going to school at that time to become an electronic technician.  So he needed to stay home and study.   Sarah is 3 years old, has had an ear infection and is on amoxicillan.  Before I leave, I make a point of telling both my hubby and Sarah that she'll need to take the medicine before she goes to bed that evening.  I leave.  What happens?  Dad gets involved with studying, Sarah decides it's time for her to take her medicine, so she tells her dad.  He says, &quot;Wait a minute.&quot;  But when you are 3 years old a minute is absolutely forever, right??  She waits, but he doesn't notice or stop.  She goes into the kitchen, gets into the refrigerator, opens the bottle (this is supposed to be a child-proof bottle??),  She proceeds to drink the whole bottle of amoxicillan, puts the cap back ON the bottle, puts it back in the refrigerator.  After an unspecified amount of time, my husband goes to the refrigerator to find an empty bottle of amoxicillan.  Sarah declares, &quot;I took my medicine!&quot;  <br>
Husband then proceeds to call the poison control center, they calmly and sweetly tell my husband that she should be fine.  The most that could happen is that she'll have some diarrhea, but to NOT give her any more of the amoxicillan. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :doh --><img src=http://www.geocities.com/bat3193/smiley1/11doh.gif ALT=":doh"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I walked back in the house at the end of the story, husband has just gotten off the phone, Sarah is crying.  She doesn't understand that her dad was just worried sick, and my husband's eyes are wide and wild, hair in a mess from him brushing it up with his hand, Sarah in his arms.  The moral of the story?   1. Never ever believe child-proof caps are child-proof.  2. A child of 3 does not have any patience. And 3. Never tell your child they need to take their medicine, just give it to them when necessary.<br>
<br>
It is funny, you have to realize how independent Sarah was at age 3 to be able to do all of that.  As far as grey hair, you've seen mine? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But I say you deserve an 'A', you didn't panic, you did what you could, that didn't work so you went to where you could get help.  Isn't that all any of us can do?  I loved the story though, thanks for posting it. <br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
