<br>
Both my wife and I are Advanced Level First Aid Instructors (in Canada that would be training roughly equal to an EMT-B in the U.S.) and we both have a program called ePocrates on our PDA handhelds that give drug information including which ones don't mix.<br>
<br>
With all that, it is nice to know that we could pretty much treat anything our son could do to himself and we also know when to get help vs. when a trip to the doctor would really be pointless.<br>
<br>
The agency we teach for has an agreement with the main paediatric hospital in our city to run &quot;baby safe&quot; courses for parents of newborns who had to spend time in the neo-natal ICU.  Before they are allowed to take the child home, they have to take the course.  This may sound overboard, but I really think every parent should know basic first aid for infants and children.  There are certain situations where that 5 or 10 minute interval before paramedics arrive can mean life or death but where knowing what to do can prevent the death during that time.<br>
<br>
